    "## Motivation and Methodology:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "da4da119",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As college students running on very little energy with an expectation of being constantly productive, we were curious of how your mocha latte or daily Monster affects how much you get done in a day. For our group project, we chose to study caffeine consumption and its relationship to productivity. As this is a relatively broad question, we spent the first few days as a group finding various resources and data to base our research questions on. The first dataset we found was a collection of all caffeinated beverages with variables that included the country, year, volume consumed and GDP. The next data set included hours worked, with similar variables, except it included a total hours worked variable. The last dataset, GDP, had information on the amount of Gross Domestic Product that each country produced which we will use as a measure of productivity.  \n",
    "\n",
    "After deciding on three separate datasets, our research questions are as follows:\n",
    "1. How does caffeine consumption (volume) and revenue relate to hours worked?\n",
    "    - Can we predict GDP using coffee and energy drinks revenue and Volume?\n",
    "2. How does caffeine consumption (volume) and revenue relate to productivity (measured by GDP)?\n",
    "    - Can we predict hours worked using coffee and energy drinks revenue and volume?\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "Since we are a relatively large group, we chose to separate caffeine consumption into two different categories: Energy Drinks and Coffee. We also chose this because energy drinks have become much more popular in recent years and we were curious to see how they compared to the standard coffee consumption. We were not fortunate enough to find any data that included both caffeine and productivity, which is why we have several different datasets provided. To minimize the amount of data we were viewing, we researched the top importers and exporters of caffeine. \n",
    "\n",
    "The following countries were found: \n",
    "- Top Exporters: Brazil , Vietnam, Colombia , Indonesia , Ethiopia, Honduras\n",
    "- Top Importers: U.S. , Germany, Japan, France, Italy, Russia\n",
    "\n",
    "Available Countries In the Datasets:\n",
    "- Colombia, U.S., Germany, Japan, France, Italy\n",
    "\n",
    "The overall process of this project is to clean the data as a whole, dividing our group into 2 subgroups: coffee and energy drinks, answering two of the four research questions provided using various data analysis and modeling techniques. We will then come back together and compare our results from each type of caffeine. \n"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "#get the world country data\n",
    "url = 'https://raw.githubusercontent.com/python-visualization/folium/master/examples/data'\n",
    "country_shapes = f'{url}/world-countries.json'\n",
    "#create dict about 12 countries location\n",
    "country = {\"name\":[\"United States\",\"Brazil\",\"Colombia\",\"Germany\",\"Ethiopia\",\"France\",\"Honduras\",\"Indonesia\",\"Italy\",\"Japan\",\"Russia\",\"Vietnam\"],\n",
    "           \"latitude\":[37.09024,-14.235004,4.570868,51.165691,9.145,46.227638,15.199999,-0.789275,41.87194,36.204824,61.52401,14.058324],\n",
    "           \"longitude\":[-95.712891,-51.92528,-74.297333,10.451526,40.489673,2.213749,-86.241905,113.921327,12.56738,138.252924,105.318756,108.277199]}"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 67,
   "id": "cff7bbae",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def maps(datas,used_column,map_name,name_legend):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Creates map with certain countries' data \n",
    "    \n",
    "    Parameters\n",
    "    ----------\n",
    "    datas : \n",
    "        data used for mapping \n",
    "        \n",
    "    used_column : \n",
    "        the features be used as parameters of map in data\n",
    "\n",
    "    map_name : \n",
    "        name of map\n",
    "    \n",
    "    name_legend:\n",
    "        name of legend\n",
    "        \n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    datas.replace('United States', \"United States of America\", inplace = True)\n",
    "    datas.replace('Russian Federation', \"Russia\", inplace = True)\n",
    "    p = folium.Map(location=[28.0290, 1.6667],zoom_start=2)\n",
    "    folium.Choropleth(\n",
    "    #The GeoJSON data to represent the world country\n",
    "    geo_data=country_shapes,\n",
    "    name=map_name,\n",
    "    data=datas,\n",
    "    #The column aceppting list with 2 value; The country name and  the numerical value\n",
    "    columns=used_column,\n",
    "    key_on='feature.properties.name',\n",
    "    fill_color='YlGn',\n",
    "    nan_fill_color='white',\n",
    "    legend_name=name_legend\n",
    "    \n",
    "       ).add_to(p)\n",
    "    for lat, lon, name in   zip(country['latitude'],country['longitude'],country['name']):\n",
    "    #Creating the marker\n",
    "           folium.Marker(\n",
    "    #Coordinate of the country\n",
    "           location=[lat, lon],\n",
    "    #The popup that show up if click the marker\n",
    "         popup=name\n",
    "          ).add_to(p)\n",
    "    return p\n"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7d9a207a",

   "source": [
    "# General Regression and Residuals"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 71,
   "id": "5210d4ac",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def corr(data):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Takes a dataframe and returns an annotated correlation matrix. \n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    return sns.heatmap(data.corr(), annot = True)\n",
    "\n",
    "def linear_regression(country,data_1,data_2,x_label,y_label,axs_x,axs_y):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Creates a subplot of linear regression graphs. \n",
    "    \n",
    "    Parameters\n",
    "    ----------\n",
    "    country : \n",
    "        A list of countries. \n",
    "        \n",
    "    data_1 : \n",
    "        The x-variable of the regression.\n",
    "\n",
    "    data_2 : \n",
    "        The y-variable of the regression.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    x_label:\n",
    "        The x-label for the plot.\n",
    "        \n",
    "    y_label:\n",
    "        The y-label for the plot.\n",
    "        \n",
    "    axs_x:\n",
    "        The number of rows in the subplot.\n",
    "        \n",
    "    axs_y:\n",
    "        The number of columns in the subplot. \n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    fig, axs = plt.subplots(axs_x, axs_y,figsize=(11, 11))\n",
    "    plot_x = []#the x axs of each graph \n",
    "    plot_y = []#the y axs of each graph\n",
    "    for i in range(axs_x):\n",
    "        for j in range(axs_y):\n",
    "            plot_x.append(i)\n",
    "            plot_y.append(j)\n",
    "     #put x axs, y axs, and country name into one dataframe\n",
    "    graph = {0:plot_x,1:plot_y,2:country}\n",
    "    graph = pd.DataFrame(graph)\n",
    "    for i in graph.index:\n",
    "     #12 graphs about each country's GDP vs coffee volume\n",
    "        axs[graph[0][i],graph[1][i]].scatter(data_1[graph[2][i]],data_2[graph[2][i]])\n",
    "        constant = sm.add_constant(data_1[graph[2][i]])\n",
    "        model = sm.OLS(data_2[graph[2][i]],constant)\n",
    "        result = model.fit()\n",
    "        #regressions of 12 countries with relationship between GDP and coffee_volume\n",
    "        axs[graph[0][i],graph[1][i]].plot(data_1[graph[2][i]],result.predict(),c=\"r\",label=\"r^2=\"+str(round(result.rsquared,2)))\n",
    "        axs[graph[0][i],graph[1][i]].set_title(graph[2][i])\n",
    "        axs[graph[0][i],graph[1][i]].set_xlabel(x_label)\n",
    "        axs[graph[0][i],graph[1][i]].set_ylabel(y_label)\n",
    "        axs[graph[0][i],graph[1][i]].legend()\n",
    "    for ax in axs.flat:\n",
    "        ax.label_outer()\n",
    "        \n",
    "def resdiual(x,y,name):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Creates the residual plots for the regression of x and y. \n",
    "    \n",
    "    Parameters\n",
    "    ----------\n",
    "    x : \n",
    "        The x-variable of the regression.\n",
    "        \n",
    "    y : \n",
    "        The y-variable of the regression.\n",
    "        \n",
    "    name: \n",
    "        The name of the x-variable. \n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    constant = sm.add_constant(x)\n",
    "    model = sm.OLS(y,constant)\n",
    "    result = model.fit()\n",
    "    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))\n",
    "    fig = sm.graphics.plot_regress_exog(result, name, fig=fig)"
   ]
  },

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "057712b3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Linear Results and Data Predictions"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 79,
   "id": "4d183222",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#remove all comma from Japan and US\n",
    "for i in range(1,len(US[\"Coffee Volume\"])+1):\n",
    "      US[\"Coffee Volume\"][i]=re.sub(\"[^\\d\\.]\", \"\", US[\"Coffee Volume\"][i])\n",
    "      US[\"Energy Drink Volume\"][i]=re.sub(\"[^\\d\\.]\", \"\", US[\"Energy Drink Volume\"][i])\n",
    "      Japan[\"Energy Drink Volume\"][i]=re.sub(\"[^\\d\\.]\", \"\", Japan[\"Energy Drink Volume\"][i])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 31,
   "id": "bb48b68d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class Pred:\n",
    "    def __init__(self,country,time):\n",
    "    '''\n",
    "    Creates a table of prediction result and correlation of prediction \n",
    "    \n",
    "    Parameters\n",
    "    ----------\n",
    "    country : \n",
    "        a dataframe of certain country \n",
    "        \n",
    "    time : \n",
    "        how many years you want to use as parameters to predict \n",
    "\n",
    "    '''\n",
    "        #clean and seperate data into train and test\n",
    "        import seaborn as sns\n",
    "        import statsmodels.api as sm\n",
    "        self.country=country\n",
    "        self.time=time\n",
    "        self.train = self.country.iloc[:self.time,:]\n",
    "        self.test = self.country.iloc[self.time:,:]\n",
    "        self.data = self.country.drop(columns=[\"Country\"])\n",
    "        self.Predict = {}\n",
    "        self.Predict2 = {}\n",
    "        #change data from object to float\n",
    "        for i in self.data.keys():\n",
    "            self.train[i]=pd.to_numeric(self.train[i])\n",
    "            self.test[i]=pd.to_numeric(self.test[i])\n",
    "    def GDP(self):\n",
    "        #Predict GDP by other features\n",
    "        self.Predict={}\n",
    "        predictor = [\"Energy Drink Revenue\",\"Energy Drink Volume\",\"Coffee Revenue\",\"Coffee Volume\"]\n",
    "        for i in predictor:\n",
    "            constant = sm.add_constant(self.train[i])\n",
    "            model = sm.OLS(self.train[\"GDP\"],constant)\n",
    "            result = model.fit()\n",
    "            new_constant=sm.add_constant(self.test[i])\n",
    "            self.Predict[\"Predict GDP by \"+i]=list(result.predict(new_constant).values)\n",
    "        self.Predict=pd.DataFrame(self.Predict)\n",
    "        self.Predict[\"Real GDP\"]=list(self.test[\"GDP\"].values)\n",
    "        self.Predict[\"time\"]=[\"2019\",\"2020\"]\n",
    "        self.Predict=self.Predict.set_index(\"time\")\n",
    "        return self.Predict\n",
    "    def Work_Hours(self):\n",
    "        #Predict Work hours by other features\n",
    "        self.Predict2 = {}\n",
    "        predictor = [\"Energy Drink Revenue\",\"Energy Drink Volume\",\"Coffee Revenue\",\"Coffee Volume\"]\n",
    "        for i in predictor:\n",
    "            constant = sm.add_constant(self.train[i])\n",
    "            model = sm.OLS(self.train[\"Hours Worked\"],constant)\n",
    "            result = model.fit()\n",
    "            new_constant=sm.add_constant(self.test[i])\n",
    "            self.Predict2[\"Predict Hours Worked by \"+i]=list(result.predict(new_constant).values)\n",
    "        self.Predict2=pd.DataFrame(self.Predict2)\n",
    "        self.Predict2[\"Real Hours Worked\"]=list(self.test[\"Hours Worked\"].values)\n",
    "        self.Predict2[\"time\"]=[\"2019\",\"2020\"]\n",
    "        self.Predict2=self.Predict2.set_index(\"time\")\n",
    "        return self.Predict2\n",
    "    def summary(self,y,x):\n",
    "        #if you want to know any result summary by any values, use this funcion. x and y should be the column's names,like GDP or Coffee Revenue.\n",
    "        self.y = y\n",
    "        self.x = x\n",
    "        constant = sm.add_constant(self.train[self.x])\n",
    "        model = sm.OLS(self.train[self.y],constant)\n",
    "        result = model.fit()\n",
    "        return result.summary()\n",
    "    \n",
    "    \n",
    "    def corr_GDP (self):\n",
    "        #correlation of GDP with its predictors\n",
    "        ax = plt.axes()\n",
    "        sns.heatmap(self.Predict.corr(), ax = ax)\n",
    "\n",
    "        ax.set_title(self.country[\"Country\"][1])\n",
    "        return plt.show()\n",
    "    def corr_Work_Hours(self):\n",
    "        #correlation of work hours with its predicotrs\n",
    "        ax = plt.axes()\n",
    "        sns.heatmap(self.Predict2.corr(), ax = ax)\n",
    "\n",
    "        ax.set_title(self.country[\"Country\"][1])\n",
    "        return plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 32,
   "id": "7fef6158",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#put each country data into Pred function\n",
    "C = Pred(Colombia,4)\n",
    "U = Pred(US,5)\n",
    "I = Pred(Italy,5)\n",
    "F = Pred(France,5)\n",
    "J = Pred(Japan,5)\n",
    "G =Pred(Germany,5)\n",
    "countries=[C,U,I,F,J,G]"
   ]

    "#the regression summary of GDP and energy drink revenue for each countries(6)\n",
    "for i in countries:\n",

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f59e5f4a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Limitations\n",
    "We had a few limitations while we worked to solve our research questions. Since we did not have much data, we couldnt run sklearns test train split, we had to do it manually which added time. When we created our models, we found that they did not have constant variance, showing us that a linear model was not the right model for this problem. In addition, our data was not most representative of what we wanted to measure. Since our data had hours worked and GDP organized by country, not people, we couldnt take into account any other factors that can contribute to GDP and hours worked."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "25dd8df7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Conclusions"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e2d70d61",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "After analyzing our results, we came to an overarching conclusion that there is some relationship between caffeine consumption, productivity, and hours worked; however, not all countries provided a linear relationship and therefore further analysis must be done to confirm this relationship. Some countries predictions for 2019 and 2020 were close, but due to the lack of data for GDP and Hour Worked datasets we are unsure of the accuracy of our results."
   ]
  },
